  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are a number of international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These are not typically \"laws\" in the sense of being passed by a single global legislature, but rather agreements and standards that countries adopt and implement domestically. Here are some of the most significant:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This convention was one of the first major international efforts to address money laundering, specifically in connection with drug trafficking. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of drug money and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: This convention expands the scope of the 1988 convention to include money laundering related to a wider range of serious crimes, not just drug trafficking. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from these crimes and to take measures to prevent and combat money laundering.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention focuses on corruption-related money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from corruption offenses and to take measures to prevent and combat such laundering.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: The FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards and promotes the effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF's 40 Recommendations are the internationally recognized standard for AML/CFT (Anti-Money Laundering/Combating the Financing of Terrorism) measures. While the FATF Recommendations are not legally binding treaties, they are highly influential, and countries are expected to implement them. The FATF also monitors countries' compliance with the recommendations and publishes reports on their progress.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (CETS No. 198)**: This convention focuses on measures to prevent and combat money laundering and terrorist financing. It covers a broad range of issues, including the criminalization of money laundering and terrorist financing, the confiscation of proceeds of crime, and international cooperation.\n\nIt is important to note that these international laws and conventions establish a framework for countries to adopt and implement their own domestic laws and regulations to combat money laundering. The specific laws and regulations vary from country to country, but they are generally based on the principles and standards set forth in these international agreements.",
